	<item>
		<title>By: ElectricBassDiver</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-tips/how-to-prepare-for-a-remote-recording-session.html#comment-16373</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[ElectricBassDiver]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 04 Sep 2015 17:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11657#comment-16373</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Hi Scott, I am using exactly the same approach since 1 year. My bandmats love this kind of structured teardown of songs they want&#039;t to cover and/or practice. 
I swear we saved soo much time and confusion with  this setup. It  speeds up rehearsal and workout  of  parts where no one has any guess what is going on. 

Reconstucting a missing timesignature and tempo is the harderst and the most time consuming part for me,
but it&#039;s worth to take the time for this step even when there are tempo-changes or signature-changes.
The benefit of this analysis is that you get familiar with the song and while doing this I automatically memorize the guts.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Hi Scott, I am using exactly the same approach since 1 year. My bandmats love this kind of structured teardown of songs they want&#8217;t to cover and/or practice.<br />
I swear we saved soo much time and confusion with  this setup. It  speeds up rehearsal and workout  of  parts where no one has any guess what is going on. </p>
<p>Reconstucting a missing timesignature and tempo is the harderst and the most time consuming part for me,<br />
but it&#8217;s worth to take the time for this step even when there are tempo-changes or signature-changes.<br />
The benefit of this analysis is that you get familiar with the song and while doing this I automatically memorize the guts.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
